                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Abombination</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-06</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Words Can't express just how aweful these movies are compared to the books.  I have been a Harry potter fan almost since the begining.  The books have and continue to be a beautiful source of inspiration for me.  But the films fall utterly short of even mediocre.  I understand that there must be changes when a book is adapted for film but too many vital complex characters, such as Hagrid and Ron, are reduced to one-dimensional comic relief.  Every character lost at least one-dimension - even harry.  I felt that if I hadn't read the book I probably wouldn't understand the movie.
<br />Not is only a horrible adaptation, it is horrible as a film.  The actors feel as if they're either trying to hard, or don't know what they're doing.  Daniel Radcliff has to gasp before every line!  The corniness was almost too much to bear.  I felt embarressed for the actors.
<br />The special effects sucked.  The troll in the girls bathroom should have at least  looked convincing.  The trees in the forbidden forest were too far apaart to be menacing.
<br />I  will say though, that Argus Filch the caretaker was portrayed beautifully.  The one star I give this film is for him.</span>
                  
              
